  <!-- ── Synopsis ── -->
  <h2 id="synopsis">Synopsis</h2>

  <p>Dolphin Centrifuge, based in Warren, Michigan, supplies purpose-built disc stack centrifuge systems for this application at 24248 Gs with separation down to 0.5 microns. Yellow grease &mdash; also known as <strong>used cooking oil (UCO)</strong> &mdash; is one of the most widely collected and recycled fats in the United States. Rendering companies and UCO collectors process millions of gallons annually, supplying feedstock for biodiesel production, animal feed supplements, and oleochemical manufacturing. The quality of the finished product directly determines its market value, making efficient purification critical to profitability.
  </p>

  <p>
    This case study documents how a large mid-west UCO collection company replaced its legacy heating-and-settling process with a <strong>DMPX-042 self-cleaning disc stack centrifuge</strong> from Dolphin Centrifuge. The results: a <strong>30% increase in throughput</strong>, dramatically cleaner product, and full return on investment in less than six months.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Customer Background ── -->
  <h2 id="customer-background">Customer Background</h2>

  <p>
    The customer is a large <strong>used cooking oil collection company</strong> based in the mid-west United States. At the time of this project, the company was processing approximately <strong>6 million gallons per year</strong> of yellow grease collected from restaurants, food processors, and institutional kitchens across a multi-state region.
  </p>

  <p>
    Like most UCO collectors, the company&rsquo;s revenue depends on the quality of its purified product. Buyers &mdash; primarily biodiesel producers and animal feed manufacturers &mdash; pay premium prices for yellow grease that meets strict specifications for moisture, impurities, and free fatty acid (FFA) content. Any water, sludge, or solid contaminants remaining in the finished product reduce its grade and market price.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Previous Method ── -->
  <h2 id="previous-method">Previous Method: Heating &amp; Settling</h2>

  <p>
    Before installing the centrifuge, the customer relied on a traditional <strong>heating and gravity settling</strong> process to purify incoming yellow grease:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>Incoming UCO was pumped into large heated settling tanks</li>
    <li>The oil was heated to reduce viscosity and held at temperature for extended periods</li>
    <li>Water and heavy solids settled to the bottom of the tank under gravity</li>
    <li>Purified oil was drawn off the top of the tank</li>
    <li>Tank bottoms (water, sludge, and trapped oil) were periodically drained and disposed of</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    This method suffered from several significant limitations:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Slow processing:</strong> Gravity settling required hours to days of residence time per batch, severely limiting throughput capacity</li>
    <li><strong>High energy costs:</strong> Maintaining large volumes of oil at elevated temperature for extended periods consumed significant energy</li>
    <li><strong>Oil loss in tank bottoms:</strong> The sludge layer at the bottom of each settling tank trapped a substantial volume of recoverable oil that was lost during drain-off. This represented a direct financial loss on every batch.</li>
    <li><strong>Inconsistent quality:</strong> Settling alone could not remove fine solids, emulsified water, or the rag layer, resulting in variable product quality from batch to batch</li>
    <li><strong>Large footprint:</strong> Multiple settling tanks occupied significant floor space and required regular manual cleaning</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The company recognized that gravity settling had reached its practical limit and began evaluating centrifugal separation as an alternative.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Centrifuge Selection & Testing ── -->
  <h2 id="centrifuge-selection">Centrifuge Selection &amp; Lab Testing</h2>

  <p>
    Before committing to a full-scale installation, the customer shipped representative samples of their yellow grease feedstock to <strong>Dolphin Centrifuge&rsquo;s testing facility</strong> for lab-scale evaluation. Our engineers conducted a series of separation trials to determine the optimal processing parameters.
  </p>

  <h3>Test Protocol</h3>
  <p>
    The lab tests were designed to establish three critical parameters: optimum processing temperature, achievable throughput rate, and expected product quality. Testing was performed on a bench-scale disc stack centrifuge using the customer&rsquo;s actual feedstock.
  </p>

  <h3>Key Findings</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Optimum temperature:</strong> 180&deg;F &mdash; this temperature provided the best balance of viscosity reduction and separation efficiency. Below 160&deg;F, throughput dropped significantly due to higher oil viscosity. Above 200&deg;F, there was no meaningful improvement.</li>
    <li><strong>Simulated throughput:</strong> At 180&deg;F, the test results were scaled to predict a production capacity of <strong>40 GPM</strong> on a full-size DMPX-042 centrifuge</li>
    <li><strong>Product quality:</strong> The centrifuge-processed oil showed dramatically lower moisture and impurity levels compared to the customer&rsquo;s gravity-settled product</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Based on these results, the <strong>DMPX-042 self-cleaning disc stack centrifuge</strong> was selected as the optimal machine for this application. Its large sludge space and high throughput capacity made it the right fit for the customer&rsquo;s 6+ million gallon annual volume.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Test Results ── -->
  <h2 id="test-results">Test Results</h2>

  <p>
    The lab-scale centrifuge testing produced results that far exceeded the customer&rsquo;s existing gravity-settled product quality:
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Parameter</th>
        <th>Gravity Settling</th>
        <th>DMPX-042 Centrifuge</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Residual Water</td>
        <td>0.5&ndash;2.0%</td>
        <td>&lt;0.05%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Sludge in Product</td>
        <td>Present (variable)</td>
        <td>None detectable</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Product Clarity</td>
        <td>Hazy / variable</td>
        <td>Clear, bright</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Processing Time</td>
        <td>Hours to days</td>
        <td>Single-pass (continuous)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Oil Recovery from Sludge</td>
        <td>Poor &mdash; oil trapped in tank bottoms</td>
        <td>Excellent &mdash; minimal oil in centrifuge sludge</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>
    The most significant improvement was the elimination of sludge in the finished product and the reduction of residual water to below 0.05%. This level of purity exceeded the requirements of the customer&rsquo;s buyers, opening the door to premium pricing.
  </p>

